'''''Bullets Over Broadway the Musical''''' is a [[jukebox musical]] written by [[Woody Allen]], based on his and Douglas McGrath's film ''[[Bullets over Broadway]]'' about a young playwright whose first Broadway play is financed by a gangster. The score consists of [[jazz standards|jazz]] and [[pop standards|popular standards]] of the years between [[World War I]] and about 1930 by various songwriters. It received its premiere on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], in 2014, at the [[St. James Theatre]], and closed on August 24, 2014 after over a hundred performances.<ref>[http://bulletsoverbroadway.com/ ''Bullets Over Broadway'' website]</ref>

==Production==
''Bullets Over Broadway the Musical'' premiered on Broadway at the [[St. James Theatre]] on March 11, 2014 in previews, officially opening on April 10, 2014. Directed and choreographed by [[Susan Stroman]], the cast features [[Marin Mazzie]] (as Helen Sinclair), [[Zach Braff]] (as David Shayne), [[Nick Cordero]] (as Cheech), [[Karen Ziemba]] (as Eden Brent), [[Vincent Pastore]] (as Nick Valenti), and [[Brooks Ashmanskas]] (as Warner Purcell). Scenic design is by [[Santo Loquasto]], costumes by [[William Ivey Long]], lighting by [[Donald Holder]], sound by Peter Hylenski, musical arrangements and supervision by [[Glen Kelly]] and orchestrations by [[Doug Besterman]].<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/186325-Woody-Allen-Musical-Bullets-Over-Broadway-With-Zach-Braff-and-Marin-Mazzie-Begins-March-11 "Woody Allen Musical ''Bullets Over Broadway'', With Zach Braff and Marin Mazzie, Begins March 11"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408045056/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/186325-Woody-Allen-Musical-Bullets-Over-Broadway-With-Zach-Braff-and-Marin-Mazzie-Begins-March-11 |date=April 8, 2014 }} playbill.com, March 11, 2014</ref>

The musical contains [[jazz standards|jazz]] and [[pop standards|popular standards]] from the years between World War I and about 1930, with additional lyrics written by Glen Kelly.<ref>Gordon, David. [http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/reviews/04-2014/bullets-over-broadway_68202.html "Reviews. ''Bullets Over Broadway'' "], theatermania.com, April 10, 2014</ref>

The musical closed on August 24, 2014, after 156 performances and 33 previews.<ref>Gans, Andrew and Hetrick, Adam. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/curtain-comes-down-on-woody-allen-musical-bullets-over-broadway "Curtain Comes Down on Woody Allen Musical ''Bullets Over Broadway'' "] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826114933/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/curtain-comes-down-on-woody-allen-musical-bullets-over-broadway# |date=August 26, 2014 }} playbill.com, August 24, 2014</ref>

A touring production started in October 2015. It had a two-week stop at [[Playhouse Square]] in Cleveland, Ohio from October 6–18.<ref>[http://broadway.playhousesquare.org/bullets-over-broadway ''Bullets Over Broadway''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402092816/http://broadway.playhousesquare.org/bullets-over-broadway |date=April 2, 2015 }} broadway.playhousesquare.org</ref> This was a non-Equity tour, directed by Jeff Whiting.<ref>Gans, Andrew. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/stops-announced-for-bullets-over-broadway-tour-345627 "Stops Announced for 'Bullets Over Broadway' Tour"] playbill.com, April 1, 2015</ref>

The first high school production in the United States opened April 28, 2017 and closed May 7, 2017 at Santa Barbara High School in Santa Barbara, Ca.  It was directed by Otto Layman, with Musical Direction by Dr. Jon Nathan,  Choreography by Christina McCarthy, and Costume Design by Bonnie Thor.  The set was designed by Otto Layman and Jonathan Mitchell, with Lights designed by Mike Madden.

==Background==
The musical is based on the 1994 film ''[[Bullets over Broadway]]'', which had a screenplay by [[Woody Allen]] and [[Douglas McGrath]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/apr/06/woody-allen-bullets-over-broadway-mia-farrow-abuse-allegation | title=The backstage dramas behind Woody Allen's Bullets Over Broadway musical | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=April 6, 2014 | accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref> Work on a musical version of ''Bullets'' started in 2000, with [[Marvin Hamlisch]] and [[Craig Carnelia]] writing the music and Allen writing the book. In 2003, Hamlisch confirmed that work on the musical was proceeding.<ref>[[Simonson, Robert]]. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/80729-Work-Continues-of-Musical-Version-of-Bullets-Over-Broadway Work Continues of Musical Version of ''Bullets Over Broadway'' "] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224142919/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/80729-Work-Continues-of-Musical-Version-of-Bullets-Over-Broadway |date=December 24, 2013 }}, playbill.com, July 17, 2003</ref>

In an interview on the opening night of the musical in April 2014, Allen said that he had resisted turning the film into a musical for years, having no interest in it as a musical. However, his sister Letty Aronson thought that it could be done as a period musical, and Allen then became interested. Marvin Hamlisch had played a few of the new songs for Allen, but Allen did not think they were right for the musical. His sister then proposed the idea of using songs of the 1920s, "and it suddenly came to life." Susan Stroman was brought into the creative team two years before the opening.<ref>Haun, Harry. [http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189952-PLAYBILL-ON-OPENING-NIGHT-Bullets-Over-BroadwayGuys-and-Dorks "Playbill On Opening Night: ''Bullets Over Broadway'' – Guys and Dorks"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502005554/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/189952-PLAYBILL-ON-OPENING-NIGHT-Bullets-Over-BroadwayGuys-and-Dorks |date=May 2, 2014 }}, playbill.com, April 11, 2014</ref>

Celebrities such as [[Barbara Walters]], [[Regis Philbin]], and [[Diane Wiest]] showed up on opening night.

==Plot==
{{expand section|date=April 2014}}
In 1929, playwright David Shayne is finally getting his first play ''God of Our Fathers'' produced on Broadway. The producer, Julian Marx, has enlisted the wealthy gangster Nick Valenti to pay for the show. Valenti wants to have his dim-witted and untalented girlfriend, Olive Neal, star as one of the leads. Valenti has assigned his strong-arm gangster Cheech to watch over Olive.  Surprisingly, Cheech comes up with great ideas for improving the play.  However, aging diva Helen Sinclair, the real star of the show, romances the younger David, who already has a girlfriend, Ellen. Meanwhile, the leading man, Warner Purcell, has his eye on Olive.

